Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Markov method", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8144506624191775`*^9, 
  3.8144506889432435`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0f163627-b106-4ac7-b3b5-\
15081238b4eb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that the method used by SequencePredict is the ",
 StyleBox["Markov",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " method. In plain terms, the model used here assumes that the probability \
of an element in the sequence only depends on the previous element in the \
sequence. \n\nI will not cover the details of the method in detail here.\n\n\
If you are familiar with conditional probability: Given a sequence of \
observations ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["X", "1"], ",", 
     SubscriptBox["X", "2"], ",", 
     RowBox[{"...", "."}], ",", 
     SubscriptBox["X", "T"]}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1125ad70-9b1c-4cde-bda3-593d2f96ba46"],
 ", the model assumes that the probability of the sequence can be expressed \
as\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"P", "(", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["X", "1"], ",", 
       SubscriptBox["X", "2"], ",", 
       RowBox[{"...", "."}], ",", 
       SubscriptBox["X", "T"]}], "}"}], ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"P", "(", 
        SubscriptBox["X", "1"], ")"}], 
       RowBox[{"P", "(", 
        RowBox[{
         SubscriptBox["X", "2"], "|", 
         SubscriptBox["X", "1"]}], ")"}], 
       RowBox[{"P", "(", 
        RowBox[{
         SubscriptBox["X", "3"], "|", 
         SubscriptBox["X", "2"]}], ")"}]}], "..."}], 
     RowBox[{"P", "(", 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["X", "T"], "|", 
       SubscriptBox["X", 
        RowBox[{"T", "-", "1"}]]}], ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"57f57d87-f7b8-4d24-aa89-5d2e1cceb936"],
 ",\n\nwhere ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"P", "(", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["X", "t"], "|", 
     SubscriptBox["X", 
      RowBox[{"t", "-", "1"}]]}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "874ae8ea-62a3-4170-a438-aa75883b216a"],
 " is the probability of observing the value ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "t"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7a1b4a72-d82b-4097-809e-da6c132128e3"],
 " at step ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["t", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "38b7276a-2c47-4ba8-b220-63af8732115b"],
 " in the sequence given that the value ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", 
    RowBox[{"t", "-", "1"}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f0c84fc4-63e6-491c-85cd-f27ef3677d39"],
 " was observed in the previous step.\n\nThe transition matrix contains the \
quantities\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["A", "ij"], "=", 
    RowBox[{"P", "(", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["X", 
       RowBox[{"t", "+", "1"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"j", "|", 
        SubscriptBox["X", "t"]}], "=", "i"}]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"3200f82e-fdf3-43d0-b2fa-ae15bc773f4a"],
 " .\n\nIn our simple example, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "t"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f4431c6b-da11-4232-81c4-ae6a2f1dcfec"],
 " can be C or S. The ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["i", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "18b88634-39f5-4588-a74d-bc78a3fc464b"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["j", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9b1dc84e-e8a3-40c1-a97a-1a3e49d04bdf"],
 " in the transition matrix can then take values in the set {C,S}.\n\n\
Examples:\n",
 Cell[BoxData[{
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["A", "SS"], "=", 
    RowBox[{"P", "(", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["X", 
       RowBox[{"t", "+", "1"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"\"\<S\>\"", "|", 
        SubscriptBox["X", "t"]}], "=", "\"\<S\>\""}]}], ")"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["A", "SC"], "=", 
    RowBox[{"P", "(", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["X", 
       RowBox[{"t", "+", "1"}]], "=", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"\"\<C\>\"", "|", 
        SubscriptBox["X", "t"]}], "=", "\"\<S\>\""}]}], ")"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]}],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "225f74e4-36a3-43d4-9e85-bfdd8802bb07"],
 "\n\nIf interested in more technical details that are beyond the scope of \
this course, see Chapter 17 of Kevin P. Murphy \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Machine \
Learning: A Probabilistic Perspective\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] The MIT Press \
(2012).\n\nMathematica uses the Kneser-Ney smoothing method to calculate the \
elements of the transition matrix. This is a popular method for language \
modelling. Details on this are much beyond the scope of this course. If \
interested see, e.g., the following paper: Stanley F. Chen, Joshua Goodman, \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]An empirical study of smoothing techniques for \
language modeling\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote], ",
 StyleBox["Computer Speech & Language",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["13",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ", 359-394 (1999). ",
 ButtonBox["http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/\
S0885230899901286",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0885230899901286"],
     None},
  ButtonNote->
   "http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0885230899901286"]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.780148549086334*^9, 3.780148570189671*^9}, {
  3.780148608862433*^9, 3.780148617454205*^9}, {3.814438931273901*^9, 
  3.814439034782504*^9}, {3.81443909680245*^9, 3.814439121001175*^9}, {
  3.8144391751062927`*^9, 3.8144395480218887`*^9}, {3.8144396088897543`*^9, 
  3.8144397655039544`*^9}, {3.814626089738605*^9, 3.814626144480485*^9}, {
  3.8146261772581377`*^9, 3.814626223370187*^9}, {3.814626398415766*^9, 
  3.814626488573642*^9}, {3.8146299041900315`*^9, 3.8146300008566837`*^9}, {
  3.814630060905532*^9, 
  3.8146300609344907`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0ada838a-f823-4826-afce-\
9d8c8ce3aeb6"],

